@Node "CMAddEntry" "RxCManager Functions  CMAddEntry"

  @{b}CMAddEntry@{ub} - adds and entry


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = CMAddEntry(type,stem)
    <type>,<stem/V>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Add a CM entry in the Genesis global user data.

    @{i}type@{ui} defines the type of the entry to add and may be
    one of:

    o USER
    o WWW
    o FTP
    o CHAT
    o TELNET

    The entry is read from the set fields of @{i}stem@{ui};
    (see @{"Fields" LINK "Fields"}).


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    type - the type of the entry to add
    stem - where to read the contents of the entry


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean

@EndNode

@Node "CMClose" "RxCManager Functions  CMClose"

  @{b}CMClose@{ub} - closes CM


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    call CMClose()
    -


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Closes an istance of CM created with CMStart() .


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    none


  @{b}Results@{ub}
    none


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"CMStart()" link "CMStart"}

@EndNode

@Node "CMFind" "RxCManager Functions  CMFind"

  @{b}CMFind@{ub} - finds entries


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    num = CMFind(where,store,keys,askUser)
    <where>,<store/V>,[key/V],[askUser/N]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Find a CM entry, searching in @{i}where@{ui} group the AmigaDOS
    patterns @{i}keys@{ui} and writes the results in @{i}store@{ui}.

    @{i}where@{ui} can be one or more of

    o USER
    o URL
    o FTP
    o CHAT
    o TELNET
    o ALL
      all the above
    o GROUPS
      if specified, empty groups are are returned and the search
      is made in the groups choosen.

    The entries are written in @{i}stem@{ui}.0, ..., @{i}stem@{ui}.j where j is
    the result of the function minus 1.
    See @{"Fields" LINK "Fields"} for a list of the results fields.

    You can set the max number of entries returned, setting in
    @{i}store@{ui} the field MAX to a positive number. If MAX is set to x
    than up to x entries are returned.

    @{i}keys@{ui} is a stem whose fields are to be set to patterns
    function should search for. It is optional and no @{i}key@{ui} or no
    fields defined means all entry.
    See @{"Fields" LINK "Fields"} for a list of the searching fields.

    @{i}askUser@{ui} is an ARexx boolean:
    o 0 don't ask user to login (default);
    o 1 ask user to login.


  @{b}Input@{ub}
    where   - where to search
    store   - where to store results
    key     - stem with AmigaDOS patterns
    askUser - should the user login ?


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    num - the number of the entries found:
          o if GROUPS was specified, 1 means none
          o if GROUPS was NOT specified, 0 means none

@EndNode

@Node "CMFindVirtualField" "RxCManager Functions  CMFindVirtualField"

  @{b}CMFindVirtualField@{ub} - searches for virtual fields


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = CMFindVirtualField(comment,field)
    <comment>,<field>


  @{b}Funtion@{ub}

    Searches in @{i}comment@{ui} a line beginning with @{i}field@{ui} and returns
    an empty line on failure or the data after @{i}field@{ui} (and spaces
    if any) till EOL.

    This let you define virtual fields.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    comment - the string to search in, usually the Comment field
              of an entry
    field   - the name of the field to search for


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - empty string or the virtual field contents

@EndNode

@Node "CMGetEntry" "RxCManager Functions  CMGetEntry"

  @{b}CMGetEntry@{ub} - gets an entry


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    num = CMGetEntry(what,stem)
    <what>,<stem/V>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Gets an entry from the current CM data.

    You must open CM before calling this function with CMStart().

    type defines what to get, one or more of:

    o USER
    o WWW
    o FTP
    o CHAT
    o TELNET
    o MULTI
      if not supplied, data are written in "stem".
      if supplied, data are written in @{i}stem@{ui}.0,...,@{i}stem@{ui}.j where j
      is the number of the selected entries minus 1.

    See @{"Fields" LINK "Fields"} for a list of the result fields.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    what - what to get
    stem - where to sotre results


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    num - the number of the selected entries; 0 means none.

@EndNode

@Node "CMLoad" "RxCManager Functions  CMLoad"

  @{b}CMLoad@{ub} - loads CM data


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = CMLoad(file,user)
    [file],[user]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Loads a data file for the current macro. rxcmanager will use
    that data in the current macro. "file" is a data file, e.g
    user/user.data. "user" is an optional user name: data will be
    load if and only if data belongs to that user.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    file - the file to loas
    user - the file owner


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean

@EndNode

@Node "CMUserData" "RxCManager Functions  CMUserData"

  @{b}CMUserData@{ub} - loads CM data


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = CMUserData(user)
    <user>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Loads the "user" data file for the current macro.
    rxcmanager will use that data in the current macro, eccept for
    CMAddEntry() that always add the entry to the global user data.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    user - the user data to load


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean

@EndNode

@Node "CMStart" "RxCManager Functions  CMStart"

  @{b}CMStart@{ub} - starts CM


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = CMStart(attrs)
    [attrs/V]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Opens a CM istance

    In attrs you may deine some attribute:
    o FILE
    o PUBSCREEN
    o HIDEUSERS
    o HIDEWWW
    o HIDEFTP
    o HIDECHAT
    o HIDETELNET
    o CLOSE
      if 1, CM is closes at macro exit


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    attrs - the attribute for CM


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"CMClose()" link "CMClose"}

@EndNode

@Node "help" "RxCManager Functions  help"

  @{b}help@{ub} - returns a RxCManager functions help string.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    string = help(funName)
    <funName/S>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Returns the arguments types mask of the function
    @{i}funName@{ui}.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    funName - a RxCManager function name


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    string - a help string

@EndNode

@Node "Fields" "RxCManager Fields"

@{b}Fields@{ub}
@{u}                                                                 @{uu}


    @{fg shine}The searching fields@{fg text}

    The searching fields are the fields user can define in the
    @{i}key@{ui} argument of the function CMFind().

    The value of each field is an AmigaDOS pattern
    of max 64 chars (after parsing: it means about 26 chars before).

    o User
      - Name
      - Address
      - City
      - Country
      - ZIP
      - Comment
      - Alias
      - Phone
      - Fax
      - EMail
      - WWW
      - FTP
      - LastName
      - Mobile
      - ICQ
      - Company
      - BAddress
      - BCity
      - BCountry
      - BZIP
      - BPhone
      - BFax
      - BEMail
      - BJobTitle
      - BDepartment
      - BOffice
      - PGPUserID
      - BMobile
      - VisualName
      - Sex
      - Birthday
      - UseBirthday
      - Anniversary
      - UseAnniversary
      - Transparent

    o WWW
      - Name
      - WWW
      - Comment
      - WebMaster
      - EMail

    o FTP
      - Name
      - FTP
      - Comment
      - Username
      - Password
      - Local

    o CHAT
      - Channel
      - Server
      - Maintainer
      - Nick
      - WWW
      - Comment
      - Password

    o TELNET
      - Host
      - Login
      - Password
      - Comment


    @{fg shine}The result fields@{fg text}

    The result fields are the fields of written in @{i}stem@{ui} by
    CMGetEntry() and CMFind().

    o User
      - NAME
      - ADDRESS
      - CITY
      - COUNTRY
      - ZIP
      - COMMENT
      - ALIAS
      - PHONE
      - FAX
      - EMAIL
      - WWW
      - FTP
      - LASTNAME
      - MOBILE
      - ICQ
      - COMPANY
      - BADDRESS
      - BCITY
      - BCOUNTRY
      - BZIP
      - BPHONE
      - BFAX
      - BEMAIL
      - BJOBTITLE
      - BDEPARTMENT
      - BOFFICE
      - PGPUserID
      - BMOBILE
      - TYPE

      Only for CMFind():
      - GROUP
        the name of the group (empty if in main group).
      - PARENTS
        parents list separated by '/'
      - EMPTYGROUP

    o WWW
      - NAME
      - WWW
      - COMMENT
      - WEBMASTER
      - EMAIL
      - TYPE

      Only for CMFind():
      - GROUP
        the name of the group (empty if in main group).
      - PARENTS
        parents list separated by '/'
      - EMPTYGROUP

    o CHAT
      . CHANNEL
      . SERVER
      . MAINTAINER
      . NICK
      . WWW
      . COMMENT
      . PASSWORD
      - TYPE

      Only for CMFind():
      - GROUP
        the name of the group (empty if in main group).
      - PARENTS
        parents list separated by '/'
      - EMPTYGROUP

    o FTP
      . NAME
      . FTP
      . COMMENT
      . USERNAME
      . PASSWORD
      . PORT
      . RETRIES
      . LOCAL

      Only for CMFind():
      - GROUP
        the name of the group (empty if in main group).
      - PARENTS
        parents list separated by '/'
      - EMPTYGROUP

    o TELNET
      . HOST
      . PORT
      . LOGIN
      . PASSWORD
      . COMMENT

      Only for CMFind():
      - GROUP
        the name of the group (empty if in main group).
      - PARENTS
        parents list separated by '/'
      - EMPTYGROUP


    Note:

    o The field PARENTS is valid if and only if the parents string
      is less than 512 chars. If groups are so nested that their
      names list is longer than 512 chars the result is undefined.

    o The field EMPTYGROUP is a boolean, meaningfull iff in
      CMSearch() was specified GROUPS; it is 0 if the group is
      not empty 1 if the group (of name .GROUP) is empty. It is
      needed in export macros.


    @{fg shine}The set fields@{fg text}

    The set fields are the fields of @{i}stem@{ui} read by CMADDEntry():

    o USER
      - Name
      - Address
      - City
      - Country
      - ZIP
      - Comment
      - Alias
      - Phone
      - Fax
      - EMail
      - WWW
      - FTP
      - LastName
      - Mobile
      - ICQ
      - Company
      - BAddress
      - BCity
      - BCountry
      - BZIP
      - BPhone
      - BFax
      - BEMail
      - BJobTitle
      - BDepartment
      - BOffice
      - PGPUserID
      - BMobile

    o WWW
      - Name
      - WWW
      - Comment
      - WebMaster
      - EMail
      - Alias

    o FTP
      - Name
      - FTP
      - Comment
      - Username
      - Password
      - Port
      - Retries
      - Local
      - Alias

    o CHAT
      - Channel
      - Server
      - Maintainer
      - Nick
      - WWW
      - Comment
      - Password

    o TELNET
      - Host
      - Port
      - Login
      - Password
      - Comment

@EndNode

